{
  "texts": [
    "If the question concerns whether the participants looked at one of two large and well-separated areas on a computer screen, the accuracy is not likely a problem for any eye tracker.",
    "Moreover, good accuracy may be required only in part of the screen, for instance, in the center if that is where the stimulus is placed.",
    "However, if the research question concern on what letter a saccade lands in a text with small font size, perhaps no eye tracker is good enough.",
    "Second, most screen-based commercial eye-trackers have accuracies around 0.5 deg (Hooge et al., 2025), which means that this may be a number to aim for, at least for healthy and cooperative adult participants.",
    "If the accuracy is much worse, it could be that the participants did not follow the instructions (look at the targets), or that the geometry of the setup has to be adapted, for instance to work around glasses that block the view of the eyes."
  ]
}